04762nam a22006615i 9780271056517DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710565177 a10.1515/97802710565172doi  a(DE-B1597)583969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBR515b.C643 2007eb 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a973.012221 aCollins, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomeland Mythology :bBiblical Narratives in American Culture /cChristopher Collins. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: -- t1 Homeland and Its Discontents -- t2 Biblical Time and the Full Narrative Cycle -- t3 Myths of Curses, Myths of Blessings -- t4 Narratives of the Night -- t5 Abduction Narratives -- t6 Homeland Nostalgia and Holy War -- t7 Secular Modernism, Biblical Style -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince 9/11, America has presented itself to the world as a Christianist culture, no less antimodern and nostalgic for an idealized past than its Islamist foes. The master-narrative both sides share might sound like this: Once upon a time, the values of the righteous community coincided with those of the state. Home and land were harmoniously united under God. But through intellectual pride (read: science) and disobedience (read: human rights), this God-blessed homeland was lost and is now worth every drop of blood it takes, ours and others', to recover.For Americans, the prime source for this once-and-future-kingdom myth is the Bible, with its many narratives of blessings gained, lost, and regained: the garden of Eden, the covenant with Abraham, the bondage in Egypt, the exodus under Moses, the glory of David and Solomon's realm, the coming of the promised Messiah, his crucifixion, resurrection, and ascension into heaven, his apocalyptic return at the end of history, and his establishment of the earthly kingdom of God. As Homeland Mythology shows, these biblical narratives have, over time, inspired a multitude of nationalist narratives, myths ingeniously spun out to justify a number of decidedly unchristian policies and institutions-from Indian genocide, the slave trade, and the exploitation of immigrant workers to Manifest Destiny, imperial expansionism, and, most recently, preemptive war.On March 25, 2001, George W. Bush shared a bit of political wisdom: "You can fool some of the people all of the time-and those are the ones you have to concentrate on." The cynical use of religion to cloak criminal behavior is always worth exposing, but why our leaders lie to us is no longer a mystery. What does remain mysterious is why so many of us are disposed to believe their lies. The unexamined issue that this book addresses is, therefore, not the mendacity of the few, but the credulity of the many.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and culturezUnited States. 0aChristianity and politicszUnited States. 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271056517zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056517.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  